10 2. If a school police officer or employee of a school district in a county
11 whose population is 700,000 or more uses or orders the use of a chemical agent
12 or electronic stun device against a pupil or minor in a manner prohibited by
13 subsection 1, the school in which he or she is assigned or, if the board of trustees
14 of the school district has contracted with a metropolitan police department
15 created pursuant to chapter 280 of NRS or with the sheriff of that county for the
16 provision of school police officers, the metropolitan police department or sheriff’s
17 office that employs the school police officer must prepare and submit a report to
18 the school district in which the incident occurred describing:
19 (a) Measures that the school police officer or employee of a school district
20 took before the incident occurred to reduce the probability for disorder and
21 disruption; and
22 (b) Actions taken before the incident occurred to de-escalate or stabilize the
23 situation to avoid using a chemical agent or electronic stun device against a pupil
24 or minor.
25 3. The board of trustees of a school district that receives a report prepared
26 pursuant to subsection 2 shall:
27 (a) Review the report;
28 (b) Conduct an independent investigation of the incident; and
29 (c) Determine whether:
30 (1) The measures or actions described in the report were consistent with
31 any policies or procedures of the school district regarding de-escalation or the
32 use of force;
33 (2) The use of the chemical agent or electronic stun device was justified;
34 and
35 (3) To revise the policies and procedures of the school district regarding
36 de-escalation and the use of force or, if the school district contracts with a
37 metropolitan police department created pursuant to chapter 280 of NRS or with
38 the sheriff of that county for the provision of school police officers, make
39 recommendations to the metropolitan police department or sheriff for the
40 modification or adoption of policies and training procedures to prevent future
41 violations of subsection 1.
42 4. Any person who violates the provisions of subsection 1 is guilty of a
43 misdemeanor.
44 5. As used in this section:
45 (a) “Chemical agent” means any chemical which can rapidly produce
46 sensory irritation or disabling physical effects in humans, which disappear within
47 a short time following termination of exposure. The term includes, without
48 limitation, items commonly referred to as tear gas, pepper spray, pepper balls and
49 oleoresin capsicum.
50 (b) “Electronic stun device” means a device that:
51 (1) Emits an electrical charge or current that is transmitted by projectile,
52 physical contact or other means; and
53 (2) Is designed to disable a person or animal temporarily or permanently.

